[{"id":29984,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["II moves slower and has higher $\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{f}}$ value than I","II moves faster and has higher $\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{f}}$ value than I","I moves faster and has higher $\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{f}}$ value than II","I moves slower and has higher $\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{f}}$ value than I"],"answer":1,"solution":"Since, adsorption of I $>$ II, I is firmly attached to column (stationary phase). Hence, it will move slowly and will move little distance. A1so II is loosely attached to column (stationary phase). Hence, it will move faster and will move large distance.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":30023,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["(I) and (V)","(II) and (V)","(I) and (IV)","(V) and (VI)"],"answer":3,"solution":"For a compound to be aromatic it must have $(4 n+2) \\pi e^{-}$and system should be planar where $n$ is an integer. (V) and (VI) both have $4 e^{-}$and planar structure. Hence are Antiaromatic","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (26 May Online)","image":null},{"id":29961,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><msup><mrow><mn>58</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mn>120</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mn>149</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mn>151</mn></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"The structure given in question is in staggered form. Hence, the two planes are <math><mn>120</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math> apart.<br />Given difference in angle of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> bond is <math><mn>29</mn><mo>.</mo></math><br /><math><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">w</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mn>120</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>29</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>149</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29832,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/11b850fe-da4e-4084-84c1-241eaadd6a28-9894422.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 221px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/559410fe-df4c-4864-8663-ecc341c8984b-9894422_B.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 178px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6320d3a6-3ca3-4060-8ed4-deee19141d2d-9894422_C.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 221px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/34bd3c45-25bf-43fd-88ec-f1539a11a067-9894422_D.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 175px;\" />&nbsp;"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/501a9a65-4a36-4db0-91e1-2004621455c3-9894422_S.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 442px;\" />&nbsp;</p><p>Staggered conformation&nbsp;has&nbsp;the lowest&nbsp;van der Waal and torsional strain. Hydrogen atoms are equally placed and there is minimum repulsion between them. Hence, it must be most stable.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30039,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["propene","2-methyl propene","2-butene","2- methyl -2- butene"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/raxVUVwuhj_upwTy1BQWC2AaDOeO9tU9mhcR5YlXYUs.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aYwktLaP_PZGBUkKYnZxj32Zn5gAojqL2ISeMN7EhAE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":30029,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Duma's Test","Beilstein's Test","Liebig's Test","Lassigne's Test"],"answer":1,"solution":"Beilstein's test : Organic compounds containing halogens when heated over $\\mathrm{Cu}$ wire loop give blue or green colour flame due to formation of volatile copper halides.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":29949,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e2076d66-6112-4c8d-818a-b7ede7e9e647-image.png\" style=\"width: 301px; height: 173px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;carbon attached to four different group is known as chiral carbon and total nimber of chiral carbons in given molecules is 5.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29824,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["c","d","b","a"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b8540c88-2754-4c4e-90c0-77fe91ea4cbf-9895978_2.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 229px;\" /></p><p>Maximum resonating structure are possible in (c) structure. In&nbsp;(a)&nbsp;structure the carbocation is stabilised by lone pair on nitrogen as well as two double bonds in the ring. In (b) and (d) structure lone pair of nitrogen is not involved in conjugation to stabilise positive charge. So,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;group will show&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;effect.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30030,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["1, 2-Propoxide","Propylene oxide","1,2-Oxo propane","1, 2-Epoxy propane"],"answer":3,"solution":"1, 2-Epoxy propane is the correct IUPAC name of given compound.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":30048,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$A < B < C < D$","$D < B < C < A$","$D < C < B < A$","$C < D < B < A$"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":29681,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\mathrm{MF}=\\mathrm{C}_9 \\mathrm{H}_{12}$<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Yg5fdOPUO8DSpOM6ws60b9tivHy3FRu19En8K9JU3mY.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (3 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29924,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Mobility or flow of solvent system","Solubility of the compound","Length of the column or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>TLC</mi></math> Plate","Physical state of the pure compound"],"answer":3,"solution":"In chromatography technique, the purification of a compound is independent of the physical state of the pure compound.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29750,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>OH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The boiling points of aldehydes and ketones are higher than hydrocarbons and ethers of comparable molecular masses. It is due to weak molecular association in aldehydes and ketones arising out of the dipole-dipole interactions. Also, their boiling points are lower than those of alcohols of similar molecular masses due to absence of intermolecular hydrogen bonding.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29830,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Metamers are the isomers having the same molecular formula but different alkyl groups on two sides of functional groups.&nbsp;Positional isomers are constitutional isomers with the same carbon skeleton and will have the same functional group.&nbsp;&nbsp;Functional isomers are structural isomers that have the same molecular formula (that is, the same number of atoms of the same elements), but the atoms are connected in different ways so that the groupings are dissimilar.&nbsp;Tautomerism is a phenomenon where a single chemical compound tends to exist in two or more interconvertible structures that are different in terms of the relative position of one atomic nucleus which is generally the hydrogen.</p><p>A. Propanamine&nbsp;and N-&nbsp;Methylethanamine&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>and</mtext><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>NHCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ba29b4ab-0737-4163-9936-a5a2c7f9b859-9894575.PNG\" style=\"width: 469px; height: 100px;\" /></p><p>B. Hexan-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-one&nbsp;Hexan-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>-one&nbsp;</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/09317474-f6c1-44a2-9d6a-af2acacfec55-9894575_1.PNG\" style=\"width: 696px; height: 100px;\" /></p><p>C. Ethanamide Hydroxyethanimine</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/745fb194-316f-41f3-8e47-03365b2f2e22-9894575_2.PNG\" style=\"width: 579px; height: 100px;\" /></p><p>D. o-Nitrophenol&nbsp;p-nitrophenol</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f52de9fb-deef-4aef-a9fb-2e50817d0d82-9894575_3.PNG\" style=\"width: 423px; height: 140px;\" /></p><p>So, the correct option is D.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29640,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["enantiomers.","identical molecules.","diastereomers.","meso compounds."],"answer":1,"solution":"The given structures have a central carbon atom bonded to four groups: $-\\text{Br}$, $-\\text{Cl}$, $-\\text{CH}_3$, and $-\\text{Me}$.<br><br>Since $-\\text{CH}_3$ and $-\\text{Me}$ both represent the same alkyl group (methyl), the central carbon atom is bonded to two identical groups.<br><br>For a carbon atom to be a chiral center, it must be bonded to four different groups. Because this condition is not met, the central carbon is not a stereocenter and the molecule is achiral.<br><br>Both structures represent the same achiral compound (2-bromo-2-chloropropane) drawn in slightly different orientations. Therefore, they are identical molecules.<br><br>Answer: identical molecules.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29871,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f465e233-5dbd-40ba-bdd1-b5cfb8c5daba-7a47936e-cb8c-4469-a460-be6887a23b3c-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 246px;\" /></p><p>So, as we can see that the final proudct C is picric acid and it contain 7 oxygen atoms.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30038,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{C}_8 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\overline{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H}_2>\\overline{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{Cl}_3>\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3 \\overline{\\mathrm{C}}>\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2 \\overline{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H}$","$\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2 \\overline{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H}>\\overline{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{Cl}_3>\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\overline{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H}_2>\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3 \\overline{\\mathrm{C}}$","$\\overline{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{Cl}_3>\\mathrm{C}_8 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\overline{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H}_2>\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2 \\overline{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H}>\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3 \\overline{\\mathrm{C}}$","$\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3 \\overline{\\mathrm{C}}>\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2 \\overline{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H}>\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\overline{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H}_2>\\overline{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{Cl}_3$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$2^{\\circ}$ carbanion is more stable than $3^{\\circ}$ and $\\mathrm{Cl}$ is $-1$ effect group.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":29788,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Fractional distillation","Fractional distillation under reduced pressure","Distillation","Steam distillation"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Steam distillation technique is applied to separate substances which are steam volatile and are immiscible with water. It is often used to purify liquids that decompose at boiling point.</p><p>The main advantage of steam distillation over conventional distillation is that the steam distillation procedure is carried out at lower temperatures and components can be separated from a mixture below their decomposition point.<br/>The given compound is steam volatile, insoluble in water and decomposes at its boiling point. So, steam distillation techniques will be used for purification.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29810,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["C &gt; E &gt; D &gt; B &gt; A","E &gt; D &gt; C &gt; B &gt; A","D &gt; E &gt; C &gt; A &gt; B","E &gt; C &gt; D &gt; A &gt; B"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The compounds A &amp; B are alcohols, and rest of the compounds are phenols. Phenols are more acidic than alcohols. Among the A &amp;B, methyl alcohol is more acidic than tertiary butyl alcohol as alkyl groups decreases the acidic nature by electron releasing tendency. Among the phenols, the phenol with electron withdrawing group is more acidic.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>(Electron withdrawing group) group will increase the acidity, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>OCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>(Electron releasing&nbsp;group) group at para position will decrease the acidity.</p><p>So, Acidic strength&nbsp;E&gt;C&gt;D&gt;A&gt;B</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29694,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Distillation","Extraction","Sublimation","Crystallization"],"answer":2,"solution":"Phase transfer from solid to vapour directly is known as sublimation.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30013,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Nitrobenzene","Pyridine","Alanine","Diazomethane"],"answer":2,"solution":"Kjeldahl's method is not applicable for compounds containing nitrogen in nitro and azo groups and nitrogen present in the ring. Because nitrogen of these compounds does not change to ammonium sulphate under these conditions.\nHence only Alanine can be used to determine percentage of nitrogen.\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/JBGRiWdRE0WGVVC14wnM_g_HzleGpIbd63K7f0s5iTc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":29897,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1d443b9c-6f86-4150-8d01-157dc92afcef-ac094f02-01b6-4e15-b554-36de63f57244-image.png\" style=\"width: 390px; height: 212px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29917,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>sigma bonds are the strongest type of covalent chemical bond. They are formed by head-on overlapping between atomic orbitals. Sigma bonding is most simply defined for diatomic molecules using the language and tools of symmetry groups.</p><p>Mesityle oxide</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5363fdd0-1691-43b9-91e8-f105e6ea2097-image.png\" style=\"width: 279px; height: 93px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#963;</mi><mo>&#175;</mo></mover></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29654,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["III $>$ II $>$ I $>$ IV","I $>$ III $>$ IV $>$ II","III $>$ I $>$ II $>$ IV","$\\mathrm{I}>$ III $>$ II $>$ IV"],"answer":3,"solution":"Alkene stability increases with the degree of alkyl substitution on the double bond due to hyperconjugation and inductive stabilization effects.<br>Analyzing each structure:<br>I is tetrasubstituted (4 alkyl groups attached to the two sp² carbons), the most stable.<br>III appears to be a disubstituted alkene with specific geometry providing enhanced stability.<br>II is trisubstituted (3 alkyl groups and 1 hydrogen).<br>IV is also disubstituted but with different geometry, less stable than III.<br>The decreasing order of stability: tetrasubstituted > trisubstituted > disubstituted variations.<br>Therefore: I > III > II > IV.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29785,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>III</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>III</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>III</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>III</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The factors that affect the stability of a species are:<br/>Number of Covalent Bonds: More the number of covalent bonds, more will be the atoms with octet, more will be the stability.<br/>Formal Charge: The species should have the least formal charge to be stable.<br/>Charge Separation: The species should have least charge separation to be stable.<br/>Charge on Atoms: The species with negative charge on electropositive atom and positive charge on electronegative atom will be least stable.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>II</mi></math>, since neutral resonating structures are more stable than charged resonating structures.<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>III</mi></math>, since the stability of the structure with –ve charge on more electronegative atom is higher.</p><p>Also, in structure I, the octet of every element is complete.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29963,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&lt;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"Anions are more nucleophilic than neutral. So,&nbsp;<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> is least nucleophilic.<br />nucleophilicity<math><mo>&#8733;</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi></math> density<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2b4eea1a-3e78-44ad-b5f3-c35b8df41f6b-image.png\" style=\"width: 498px; height: 217px;\" /><br /><br />Greater the delocalization of charge, lesser will be nucleophilicity.<br /><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><msubsup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29769,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/17e9be78-e4d6-48bb-b804-90ad18ab62c0.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 141px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2f96012c-2eec-4c9f-93bd-da147b213d74.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 150px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/174b6a9b-1f23-4146-8a64-436af9332762.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 145px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/81306821-d19b-4678-ab4f-e880107a87ef.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 146px;\"/>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>\"4-Methyl\" indicates that there is a methyl group (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>) attached to the fourth carbon atom.</p><p>\"Pent-2-enal\" indicates that there is an aldehyde functional group (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>─</mo><mi>CHO</mi></math>) attached to the  five-carbon chain, and there is a double bond (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>─</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>─</mo></math>) between the second and third carbon atoms.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/59d76f2b-caac-4513-b227-0fa9201e7537.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 157px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30022,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Chain isomers","Functional isomers","Tautomers","Geometrical isomers"],"answer":3,"solution":"Maleic acid and fumaric acids are geometrical isomers.\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/LcBaZiZRrrFy-zeoa-NHEYC23gBYibbRuwPGq-1fnF8.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2gtPST4inN8aYZe8xtax9xErDR8_OsRibjqjDDUKSzQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (26 May Online)","image":null},{"id":29664,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true"],"answer":3,"solution":"Statement I:<br><br>Two chiral centre and due to presence of $-COOH$ compound dissolves in $NaHCO_3$.<br>Statement II:<br><br>Two $sp^3$ carbons, one $sp^2$ carbon, and one $sp$ carbon.<br>Both statements are true.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29913,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>NO</mi><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NO</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>For detection of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>,</mo></math>&nbsp;the following test is used. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi>COO</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dc6e92b8-9149-4443-a711-e5783e70707a-image.png\" style=\"width: 386px; height: 487px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29845,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>34</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>04</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>40</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>04</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>36</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>03</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>38</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>04</mn><mo>%</mo></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The Carius halogen method in analytical chemistry is a method for the quantitative determination of halogens in chemical substances. A known mass of an organic compound is heated with fuming nitric acid in the presence of silver nitrate contained in a hard glass tube known as Carius tube, in a furnace.</p><p>Mass of organic compound&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>45</mn><mi>gm</mi></math></p><p>Mass of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgBr</mi></math> obtained&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>36</mn><mi>gm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math>Moles of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgBr</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>36</mn></mrow><mn>188</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> Mass of Bromine&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>36</mn></mrow><mn>188</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>80</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1532</mn><mi>gm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>%</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Br</mi></math>&nbsp;in compound&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1532</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>45</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>34</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>04</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29912,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>,</mo><mi>sp</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>sp</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>,</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>,</mo><mi>sp</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>,</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>,</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>,</mo><mi>sp</mi><mo>,</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Hybridisation is found by steric number which is generally&nbsp;the summation of sigma bonds and lone pairs of electrons.</p><p>So as we can see&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>&nbsp;has four sigma bonds so it has&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;hybridisation.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></math>&nbsp;has three sigma bonds so it has&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;hybridisation.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29692,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["(A)-(II), (B)-(III), (C)-(IV), (D)-(I)","(A)-(II), (B)-(III), (C)-(I), (D)-(IV)","(A)-(III), (B)-(II), (C)-(I), (D)-(IV)","(A)-(III), (B)-(II), (C)-(IV), (D)-(I)"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/S5Cy9Fnqq7X7PBACG6mxuK7I0l17aVlHQu3BJhbDwgY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30069,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["carboxylic acids","diols","dialdehydes","deketones"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":30049,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2 \\dot{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H} < \\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3 \\dot{\\mathrm{C}} < \\left(\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5\\right)_2 \\dot{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H} < \\left(\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5\\right)_3 \\dot{\\mathrm{C}}$","$\\left(\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5\\right)_3 \\dot{\\mathrm{C}} < \\left(\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5\\right)_2 \\dot{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H} < \\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3 \\dot{\\mathrm{C}} < \\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2 \\dot{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H}$","$\\left(\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5\\right)_2 \\dot{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H} < \\left(\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5\\right)_3 \\dot{\\mathrm{C}} < \\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3 \\dot{\\mathrm{C}} < \\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2 \\dot{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H}$","$\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2 \\dot{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H} < \\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3 \\dot{\\mathrm{C}} < \\left(\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5\\right)_3 \\dot{\\mathrm{C}} < \\left(\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5\\right)_2 \\dot{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null}]